# Git Commit Protocol

**Only create commits when requested by the user** unless direct-development workflow is active.

## Before committing

Run in parallel:
- `git status`
- `git diff` (staged and unstaged)
- `git log` (recent messages for style)

## Commit message

- 1–2 sentences focused on **why**, not just what
- Accurately label the change (add / update / fix / refactor / test / docs)
- Use HEREDOC for the message

## Safety (never)

- Update git config
- Destructive git commands (force push, hard reset) unless explicitly requested
- Skip hooks unless explicitly requested
- Force push to `main`/`master`
- Commit secrets (`.env`, credentials)
- `git commit --amend` unless all apply: user requested OR hook auto-modified after your commit AND HEAD is yours AND not pushed
- If commit **failed** or was **rejected by hook**, fix and create a **new** commit — never amend
- Interactive git (`-i` flags)
- Empty commits when nothing changed

## After commit

Verify with `git status`. Do not push unless asked (except direct-development / deploy rules).
